<subSubSection id="C340650393708876FF63FA71FEAEF9EA" pageId="4" pageNumber="415" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE5368893708876FF63FA71FEAEF9EA" blockId="4.[173,659,1496,1729]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A93708876FF63FA71FEC7F9D1" bold="true" box="[197,301,1522,1543]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Only in the members of this species is the elytral disc adorned with reddish brown vittae (
<figureCitation id="13612A0D93708876FF56F9A4FED3F9EA" box="[240,313,1575,1596]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="12.[197,237,1672,1691]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,193,1649]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[172,1193,193,1649]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs. 61–64. Habitus. 61) Diutius gallerucoides; 62) Diutius pallidus; 63) Akonesis vittatis; 64) Akonesis pictipennis." pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Fig. 63</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C340650393708876FF63F9C1FB7CFD06" pageId="4" pageNumber="415" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE5368893708876FF63F9C1FD79F917" blockId="4.[173,659,1496,1729]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A93708876FF63F9C1FE7AF981" bold="true" box="[197,400,1602,1623]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Redescription. Size</emphasis>
: Length 10.0 mm; width 3.5 mm. 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A93708876FEAEF9DEFEABF9A4" bold="true" box="[264,321,1629,1650]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Form</emphasis>
: As in 
<figureCitation id="13612A0D93708876FE28F9DEFE32F9A4" box="[398,472,1629,1650]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="12.[197,237,1672,1691]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,193,1649]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[172,1193,193,1649]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs. 61–64. Habitus. 61) Diutius gallerucoides; 62) Diutius pallidus; 63) Akonesis vittatis; 64) Akonesis pictipennis." pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Fig. 63</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A93708876FE42F9DEFDB3F9A4" bold="true" box="[484,601,1629,1650]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Integument</emphasis>
: Cranium and pronotum yellow; elytra mostly yellow, each with 2 reddish brown vittae; femora yellow, tibiae and tarsi brown; pterothorax and abdomen
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE5368893708876FD65FF41FBE9FEA1" blockId="4.[707,1194,194,1145]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">
yellow. 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A93708876FCB6FF41FCACFF01" bold="true" box="[784,838,194,215]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13612A0D93708876FCF0FF41FC75FF01" box="[854,927,194,215]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="8.[197,238,1224,1243]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,194,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-220@8.[172,1193,193,1200]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs. 47–52. Akonesis vittatis. 47) Head, frontal view; 48) Head, ventral view; 49) Antenna; 50) Mouthparts;" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
): Eyes narrower than frons (20:25); capitular antennomeres slender (
<figureCitation id="13612A0D93708876FBF8FF5EFB77FF24" box="[1118,1181,221,242]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,215,1438,1457]" captionTargetBox="[164,1158,191,1428]" captionTargetId="figure-91@3.[151,1172,183,1428]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 1–15. Akonesis vittatis. 1) Head, frontal view; 2) Head, ventral view; 3) Head, dorsal view; 4) Pronotum; 5) Antenna; 6) Prothorax, ventral view; 7) Metathoracic wing; 8) Mandible; 9) Labium; 10) Maxilla; 11) Labrum; 12) Tegmen; 13) Phallus; 14) Metendosternite; 15) Spicular fork." pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A93708876FD65FF74FCE4FEDA" bold="true" box="[707,782,247,268]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum quadrate (70:70), lateral tubercle prominent (
<figureCitation id="13612A0D93708876FCFFFE91FC4EFEF1" box="[857,932,274,295]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[197,238,1368,1387]" captionTargetBox="[174,1163,203,1350]" captionTargetId="figure-110@6.[172,1193,183,1363]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs. 30–42. Morphological structures. 30) Akonesis vittatis, pronotum; 31) Akonesis pictipennis, pronotum; 32) Diutus pallidus, pronotum; 33) Crusbatus spinosus, pronotum; 34) D. pallidus, antenna; 35) Diutus gallerucoides, antenna; 36) C. spinosus, antenna; 37) D. pallidus, tegmen; 38) D. pallidus, phallus; 39) C. spinosus, spicular fork; 40) C. spinosus, male, pygidium; 41) C. spinosus, tegmen; 42) C. spinosus, phallus." pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
); epipleural fold gradually narrowed to elytral apex, asetiferous punctures present; 1° and 2° setae present. 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A93708876FB91FEC4FB4BFE8A" bold="true" box="[1079,1185,327,348]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation id="13612A0D93708876FCC7FEE1FC15FEA1" box="[865,1023,354,375]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,215,1438,1457]" captionTargetBox="[164,1158,191,1428]" captionTargetId="figure-91@3.[151,1172,183,1428]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 1–15. Akonesis vittatis. 1) Head, frontal view; 2) Head, ventral view; 3) Head, dorsal view; 4) Pronotum; 5) Antenna; 6) Prothorax, ventral view; 7) Metathoracic wing; 8) Mandible; 9) Labium; 10) Maxilla; 11) Labrum; 12) Tegmen; 13) Phallus; 14) Metendosternite; 15) Spicular fork." pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Figs. 12 and 13</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE5368893708876FD7DFEFFFC59FDB0" blockId="4.[707,1194,194,1145]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A93708876FD7DFEFFFCD5FE47" bold="true" box="[731,831,380,401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Variation.</emphasis>
Size: Length 10.0–12.0 mm; width 3.5–4.0 mm. In specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="F34D761893708876FBA6FE14FBD6FE7A" box="[1024,1084,407,428]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, the brown elytral vitta proximal to the elytral suture approximates the sutural margin before the sutural margin base. In Bolivian specimens, this vitta extends linearly to the elytral anterior margin. Moreover, in Bolivian specimens the two brown discal vittae conjoin posteriorly, which is not the case in Brazilian specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE5368893708876FD7DFDE8FB7CFD06" blockId="4.[707,1194,194,1145]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A93708876FD7DFDE8FC6FFD56" bold="true" box="[731,901,619,640]" pageId="4" pageNumber="415">Natural History.</emphasis>
Specimens were collected during October, November, and December; one at a blacklight at 
<quantity id="4CA29B6D93708876FCDDFD23FC56FD63" box="[891,956,672,693]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="415" unit="m" value="430.0">430 m</quantity>
elevation in a tropical transitional forest, another at 
<quantity id="4CA29B6D93708876FC46FD38FBDAFD06" box="[992,1072,699,720]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" pageId="4" pageNumber="415" unit="m" value="1.35">1,350 m</quantity>
elevation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
